    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. so if the neutrophils are the first responders for bacteria, how do the lymphocytes actually behave in a viral infection? like what is the cellular mechanism that causes the lymphocytosis to show up on the lab report?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "In a viral infection, the lymphocytes are the main players, and their appearance as lymphocytosis is a direct result of the immune system mounting a specific, targeted response. The cellular mechanism involves the activation and proliferation of these lymphocytes—specifically T-cells and B-cells—to recognize and eliminate the virus.\n\nWhen a virus enters the body, the immune system doesn't immediately flood the system with neutrophils; instead, it activates the lymphocytes. These lymphocytes multiply rapidly to create an army capable of mounting a specific adaptive immune response against the viral antigens. This proliferation leads to an increased number of lymphocytes circulating in the blood, which you see reflected as **lymphocytosis** on the lab report.",
      "source": "target",
